<section xml:id="sec-adjoint-matrix"
    xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Adjoint Matrix</title>
    <introduction xml:id="sm-introduction-adjoint-matrix">
        <p>
            <idx>
                <h>Matrices</h>
                <h>Adjoint</h>
            </idx>
            The adjoint matrix plays a crucial role in various matrix computations, including finding
            the inverse of a matrix using the formula that involves the adjoint and the determinant.
        </p>

        <p>
            The cofactor matrix is based on cofactors and minors. Sage does not have implemented methods to
            calculate cofactors and minors (Sage can only calculate directly the adjoint matrix). We will
            show in the next sections how to create our own functions in Sage to calculate minors and cofactors.
        </p>
        <p>
            The <em>adjoint</em> of a matrix <m>A</m> is the transpose of its cofactor matrix <m>C</m>:
            <m>adj(A)=C^T</m>. In Sage, the <c>adjugate()</c> method returns the adjoint matrix.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                M= matrix([
                    [1, 1, 0, 1, 2],
                    [2, 1, 1, 0, 1],
                    [1, 2, 1, 1, 0],
                    [0, 1, 2, 1, 1],
                    [1, 0, 1, 2, 1]])
                M.adjugate()
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            In the next sections, we will explore how to compute step by step the minors, cofactors, and the adjoint matrix.
        </p>
    </introduction>
</section>
